\begin_layout Standard
Maybe it's time I give in.
 I am not being unusual or unlike myself, and for sure there is no point
 in trying to be who I was when I was seventeen.
 If anything, he is the one who let me become who I am today.
 A few tears shed every morning are a small price to pay for the gifts he
 gave me.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's almost time for me to head back.
 I promised myself I would finish off that memoir today.
 My publishing agent will not be happy when she finds out I have been doing
 whatever it takes to find excuses to stop writing.
 It becomes a most difficult chore to not burn out and crash after so many
 years of not even having a chance to sit down and think.
 An author and playwright of significant reflective works doesn't have time
 to think; what irony this world beholds!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am nearing the edge of a small woodland.
 I will stop here for a bit, then I really have to get back.
 I follow the small trail through the light shrubbery and get to my special
 thinking spot.
 I sit down on the mighty rock, and look up.
 As always, the darker tones of the forest canopy bring out the brightness
 of the sky in this spot.
 There must have been some Creator out there who pities my inner turmoil
 enough to give me this place of sanctity and peace.
 The solidness of this huge boulder with a piece of the sky cut out from
 the tall thicket of trees convinces me that one day God's hand will reach
 through the trees and snatch me away from atop this rock.
 It feels strangely holy, having such an adamant belief that a supernatural
 being is going to abduct me.
 This is probably just my fascination with 
\emph on
Slaughterhouse-Five 
\emph default
messing with my head, though.
\end_layout

