\begin_layout Standard
Well, I told myself I would only stay for a bit.
 I get up and take the usual path back to my house, put my shoes in their
 usual spot, and as usual splash some water on my face.
 As usual, as usual, as usual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I look into the mirror above the sink, and observe my face once more.
 So familiar it still is; how lucky I should consider myself that the years
 have been kind to me.
 If anything, the few wrinkles I do have give me a unique charm.
 If it were not for my pure-white hair, I could probably pass off as a woman
 in my forties.
 Ah, well.
 My only explanation is that the world has already weathered my soul enough
 that giving me the aches and sores of old age would simply be salt in the
 wound.
 Or maybe it's a curse, one that ensures I have both the health to live
 a long life and the indecisiveness to not be able to end it.
 How much I would give to know if after my passing I can finally be reunited
 with him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I sit down at my desk, and begin sorting papers.
 By this point, I am just trying my hardest to get out of starting writing
 today.
 After I sort my desk to the point where I cannot possibly convince myself
 that what I am doing is meaningful or worthwhile, I finally pull out my
 laptop and open the document I was working on.
 Computers and word processors sure made my work easier since I wrote my
 first book; many sections on my drafts for that one were scribbled on the
 backs of envelopes and stapled to my error-laden typewritten work.
 But maybe it was the feeling of having to jump through a few hoops to get
 my voice out there is what made me so inspired to write like a madwoman.
 Now, with me only neeing to hit a few buttons on this newfangled contraption,
 I feel absolutely no desire to write anymore.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I find myself gazing at the piano in the corner.
 That poor thing hasn't had its beautiful sound coaxed out in decades.
 As much as I try to dabble in some small pieces, nothing I play can bring
 out the feelings he did.
 Express the simplicity and power of music like he did.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I stand up and sit down at the piano.
 This piano is truly wasted on an amateur like me, with its wonderfully
 light key action, its rich bass, and its sparkling trebles.
 A five-foot Cunningham, mahogany finish.
 Truly a beauty.
 It is truly a miracle that I managed to preserve it through all these years,
 with me being on the move all over the place and so many bouts of insanity
 leaving seemingly everything except dear Wellspring broken.
 It would have been so much easier to make my escape from the city to the
 countryside if I didn't have to find a piano mover to take my piano along,
 but I took the money out of my food budget, so here it is keeping me company.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Oh, dear Wellspring.
 Let me hear you sing.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

