\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes, I look back and think of everything as fate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Changing to a new high school for my final year was a sudden decision that
 angered my parents.
 Why would someone whose parents set on a path into mathematics, whose appearanc
e in national mathematics competitions proved their skill and promise, have
 any need to enter an arts high school?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But by some sort of crazy twist of events, I managed to convince my parents
 to sign the transfer papers.
 Getting accepted into this private arts school was easy, even though I
 had no portfolio or outstanding achievements.
 I guess even a school of this kind needs some students with high marks
 to push up the school test score averages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I would be pulling up the marks by a decent amount too, considering there
 were only ten students in the stream I chose.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Scriptwriting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 isn't that popular, I guess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first day I walked into Principium Academy is a blur in my head now.
 An orientation that lasted way too long, a welcome ceremony with absolutely
 no substance, being left all by myself after planned activities when everyone
 grouped into the little cliques they entered this school with.
 It is all a distant memory for me now, and all so insignificant to this
 story that is unfolding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But how could I forget the first time I entered the place where everything
 started?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The living quarters at this school were right beside the main campus.
 As soon as our orientation guide took us to see where we were staying,
 I immediately saw that the tuition we paid wasn't for nothing.
 A beautiful glistening lake with green grass all around it and clusters
 of housing units organized row by row overlooking it is what greeted us
 when we entered the gates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Welcome to Cartier Lake Village.
 This will be your home for the next four years.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The freshmen around me got very excited, as I recall.
 I was the only transfer student in this group, and somehow it felt strange
 to join in with them.
 I stayed silent, and did not betray just how amazed I was at the aesthetics
 of where I was spending this year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The guide talked to us about the history of the building and about the excellent
 placement of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

CLV
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but everyone was wondering the same question: 
\emph on
When can we finally go in?
\emph default
 When the guide finally let us take our leave, all of the freshman rushed
 into their rooms without even going back to the student center where our
 baggage locked.
 I remember walking back to the main campus all alone, which I would do
 every morning for the rest of the year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When I finally managed to enter my unit with a suitcase in each hand, the
 very first thing I noticed was a piano in the common room.
 Thinking back, I don't know why I didn't notice the excellent view of the
 lake from the windows, or the spacious size of the bedrooms, or the excellent
 wooden furnishings in the kitchen and eating area.
 The very first thing I thought when I entered the place where I became
 myself was, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Why is this damn piano here?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 How strange it all was.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But I didn't think much of it, and went into my assigned bedroom to unpack.
 I probably did as I would do now, unceremoniously dumping out all my clothing
 onto the floor then separating it into piles that roughly constitute a
 full outfit.
 Good thing I only have black, white, or red shirts as well as black skirts
 and pants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Six possible outfits in all," I commented.
 Probably.
 I might have also tried to calculate the probability of getting one of
 those outfits if I randomly dressed from one of those piles, but more likely
 I looked into my other suitcase and pulled out a neatly wrapped present
 for my roommate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This would be my first time having a roommate.
 I wanted everything to go perfectly, so I spent hours trying to think of
 the perfect gift.
 In the end, I decided on a care package with pens, a small corkboard, pins,
 and (this one I was proud of) a pack of stationery with words of wisdom
 carefully chosen and written by me onto every sheet.
 There was enough for my roommate to put up a new one every day for the
 rest of the school year.
 I really hope she likes it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Here is a present for you, I am happy to make your acquaintance!" I practiced
 my greeting.
 "No, no, too formal...
 Hey, this is for you, hope we get along! Better..."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I needed to get this right.
 I would be living with this person for the rest of the year, after all;
 she and I had better get along, or I would lose the chance to finally make
 a close friend.
 But at that moment, I was incredibly tired from the tour.
 I made my bed with the sheets, blanket and bedding I brought, and took
 a short nap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although that short nap was awfully long.
 When I woke up, my room was totally dark.
 I slept all the way from early afternoon to after sunset.
 My roommate must have already unpacked by this point, and probably was
 wondering what I was doing.
 I scramble to turn on the lights and check in my small mirror if I looked
 halfway presentable, then stumbled out of my room with the present in hand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lights were off in the unit.
 The other bedroom's door was slightly ajar.
 I peeked inside, then opened the room completely to confirm what I saw:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The room was completely empty except for the sheetless single bed and writing
 desk.
 Somehow, even after so many hours, my roommate still hadn't unpacked or
 even taken her baggage from the student center.
 A quick look around the unit confirmed that she wasn't in the unit at all.
 
\end_layout

